1. Introduction
It is trite law that a director owes a duty to act bona fide in the best interests of the
company in which he or she is involved.1 However, the main question that follows from
a duty formulated in this manner is what constitutes ‘the best interests of the company?’
Different theories such as the shareholder value theory, the stakeholder theory and the
enlightened shareholder value theory have all been developed to address this question.
In this paper, the development of the corporate governance debate in South Africa in
the context of the shareholder value approach, the stakeholder approach, and
proposals by the Corporate Regulation Division of the Department of Trade and Industry
during the company law reform process for the adoption of the enlightened shareholder
value approach will be discussed. Further, the paper concentrates on section 76(3)(b) of
the Companies Act 71 of 2008 which is the key provision in highlighting the interests to
considered by directors when managing companies. It also discusses sections 7, 20(4),
144, 145, 162(2), 165(2) and 218(2) which are all relevant when determining the
recognition of stakeholder interests in the Companies Act.
