and Du Plessis, 2007). It has been stated that corporate governance involves the
balancing of the interests of all internal stakeholders and other parties who can be
affected by the corporation’s conduct (Benade et al, 2008). The King Reports on
Corporate Governance for South Africa also place strong emphasis on the protection of
stakeholder interests. However, South African commentators (Botha, 1996; Spisto,
2005) argue that the King Reports are not sufficiently clear on the preferred approach
on the protection of the interests of stakeholders.
While the previous studies cited above have shown that stakeholder interests are now
important factors to which company management must have regard to, the focus has
been mainly on the King Reports. The issue whether the Companies Act, 2008 gives
recognition to a broader spectrum of stakeholders and reflects the new thinking in
corporate governance has not received much attention among researchers. Moving
beyond prior literature, this study therefore, provides a critical analysis of the corporate
governance approach in South Africa as reflected in the Companies Act.
3. Research Methodology
The qualitative research method has been employed in this study. The main methods
associated with qualitative research are participant observation, qualitative interviewing,
and the collection and qualitative analysis of texts and documents (Welman, Kruger and
Mitchell, 2006). The research method used in this study is the collection and qualitative
analysis of texts and documents. The research is mainly analytical and critical in nature.
In the context of this study, an analytical approach enables one to gain a deeper
understanding of the corporate governance approach in South Africa. The critical
approach seeks to identify the lacuna in the law.
